california.title: RAILROAD incident near Sylmar
california.descrip: Per the reporting party, Metrolink contacted Union Pacific Railroad (UPRR) because this incident occurred on their tracks, but it was a UPRR train that was involved in the incident. A vehicle was repeatedly driving into the stopped train. It was reversing and driving into the train over and over again. The freight train is number IBRLCX of the 13th, and the locomotive number is UP5929. The direction of travel was unknown. The incident occurred on a main line track. There was no railroad crossing involved. The vehicle was a white Ford pick-up truck. There were no injuries reported, and the subject fled the scene when the police arrived. There was no derailment or release of Hazmat. The main line is closed, and it is unknown when it will be open again. The tracks must be inspected. The incident is under investigation. It is suspected that the individual was stealing something from the train.

california.title: CHEMICAL incident near Hawthorne
california.descrip: Silicone oil was added to a 30-gallon container of powdered aluminum as a neutralizer in preparation for disposal. For unknown reasons, the mixture began to off-gas. The Los Angeles County Fire Department was contacted and is currently on-site, while the Health Hazardous Materials Division is en route to assist. As a precaution, the outdoor incident area has been isolated, and the facility was evacuated of its approximately 15 personnel. No staff members were exposed to the gas, and no medical care was needed. Management has remained on-site, while the other employees have been allowed to leave for the day. Fire personnel are likely to permit the off-gassing to continue while monitoring the chemical process for safety. If this course of action is taken, there is no anticipated danger to the public.

The caller states the employee never uses the recovery tank and even encourages residents to release the gas into the air before the company goes into their homes for repairs. The environmental impact is unknown. It is unknown if the release is secured. No remedial actions taken.

california.title: CHEMICAL, VAPOR incident near Bloomington

california.title: CHEMICAL incident near Bloomington
california.descrip: A loose vapor valve on a tank railcar led to an argon release into the atmosphere. At the time, the railcar was part of a stationary group of cars in the West Colton Railyard. A UPRR Hazardous Materials Manager and an environmental specialist were present at the scene. The release was unrecoverable. Technicians fixed the valve, stopping the leak, and the group of cars was put back into operation. There was no impact on railyard operations due to this incident.

california.title: SEWAGE incident near Colton
california.descrip: Per the reporting party, the lift station experienced a brief power loss, resulting in the release of approximately 20 gallons of sewage onto the concrete curb and gutter, which subsequently flowed into an open channel leading to the Santa Ana River. The responsible party reports that approximately 10 gallons of the release have been recovered. The release has been stopped and contained.

california.title: PETROLEUM incident near San Diego
california.descrip: Per the reporting party, the Harbor Police of San Diego discovered an abandoned vessel that was sinking. The Harbor Patrol's vessel unit was dewatering the vessel, and an unknown sheen was observed in the water. The sheen was caused by the partial sinking of the vessel, and it is a combination of oil and diesel fuel. There is a tow boat recovering the vessel. The sinking vessel's vessel identification number is: Z3922KF000, and it's license number is: 3922 KFN. Tow Boat USA is performing the clean-up including vessel recovery. It is a 32 foot vessel, and it's body class is C. Currently the spill is not stopped or contained.
